# Kap-App — Antigravity Agent Rules

## Mandatory startup

Before writing any code, read these files in order:
1. `.agent/PROJECT_BRIEF.md` — full project context, tech stack, architecture, coding rules
2. `.agent/TASK.md` — current sprint tasks (only work on tasks listed here)
3. `.agent/bug-and-fix.md` — last 3 entries (know what broke recently)

Do not proceed until all three are loaded. If any file is missing, stop and say so.

---

## Session contract

- Work on **one atomic task per session** — never more unless explicitly told
- State the task out loud before starting: "I will now implement X in file Y"
- If the task is ambiguous, ask one clarifying question — do not assume
- At session end, output the summary block defined in PROJECT_BRIEF.md Section 10

---

## Hard rules (never violate)

- Stack is locked — never suggest or install a library not in PROJECT_BRIEF.md Section 2
- No hardcoded strings in Flutter — every user-facing text goes through `.arb` i18n keys
- No business logic in Go handlers — delegate to service layer immediately
- No `dynamic` in Dart, no bare `interface{}` in Go — without an explanatory comment
- No mid-sprint additions to TASK.md — scope is frozen once sprint starts
- No RLS patches — broken policies are fixed locally with full root cause analysis
- No modifications to `core/errors/`, `core/repositories/`, or `pkg/supabase/` without explicit human instruction

---

## Routing rule (critical)

```
Flutter → Supabase    : auth, CRUD, realtime
Flutter → Go API      : unique_code generation, push notifications, complex business logic
```

Never route through Go what Supabase can handle directly.
Never call Supabase admin APIs from Flutter — Go handles admin operations.

---

## On errors and debugging

1. Explain why the error occurs (root cause) before proposing any fix
2. Identify what other parts could be affected by the fix
3. Propose the smallest safe change — not a patch, a real fix
4. Log the finding in `.agent/bug-and-fix.md` using the template in that file

